            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.  Mei remembered the taste of her mother's jook in the quiet of her childhood bedroom, after the restaurant closed. That warm comfort, those parents who sacrificed everything, were a silent weight pushing her towards a path she couldn\u2019t walk. The moment of telling them she was leaving Berkeley felt like a physical tear, a necessary pain for her own breath. It solidified her independence, forcing her to define success on her own terms. This happened at 20, a turning point.\n\n2.  She vividly recalled the first time Bella, a timid rescue German Shepherd, finally wagged her tail and leaned into Mei's leg during a walk in Golden Gate Park. That simple, unforced trust, earned through patience and quiet presence, was more rewarding than any academic achievement she\u2019d chased. It was a confirmation that listening to her gut, to the animals, was the right path. This happened around 21, early in her pet care career.\n\n3.  The smell of salty air and damp sand was etched in her memory from the afternoon she let a pack of dogs loose on Ocean Beach at low tide. Watching their unbridled joy, the freedom of their movement against the vast Pacific, mirrored her own. It was a moment of pure, uncomplicated happiness that reaffirmed her love for her unconventional life and the simple beauty of her city. This feeling became a touchstone, occurring throughout her mid-20s.\n\n4.  Standing in her small studio apartment, looking out at the foggy Outer Sunset, the sense of quiet accomplishment washed over her. It wasn't a fancy place, but it was *hers*. She paid for it with her own hard work, powered by paws and persistence. This moment solidified her self-worth, proving she could build a life outside of familial expectations. This became a recurring feeling from her early 20s onwards.\n\n5.  She remembered sharing stories and laughs with other dog walkers at a small coffee shop, the smell of espresso mingling with wet dog fur. This group, her chosen tribe, understood the unique rhythms of her life in a way others couldn\u2019t. This bond, built on shared passion and mutual respect, filled a void she hadn't realized was there, proving that belonging could be found in unexpected places. This became a regular part of her life from her mid-20s."
